From: Matthew Jackson <matthew@pq.io>
Subject: [PATCH 3/9] hw/display/apple-gfx-linux: MMIO dispatch

Wire the PCI BAR0 MMIO region to `lagfx_mmio_read` /
`lagfx_mmio_write` in libapplegfx-vulkan. The library is the
authoritative decoder for the register layout - it mirrors
Apple's ParavirtualizedGraphics.framework's internal
dispatch and returns a single 32-bit value per read.

`MemoryRegionOps` is configured with a 4-byte `impl` and
4..8-byte `valid` range, matching the macOS sibling.

As of the current library release (`libapplegfx-vulkan`
8edc43c), the MMIO dispatch covers the P0 and P1 opcode
families (NOP, Debug, GetDeviceInfo, DefineTask2,
DeleteTask, DefineChildFIFO, DeleteChildFIFO,
SynchronizeResources, MapMemory2, UnmapMemory,
ExecIndirect2) plus the display-plane opcodes (DisplayAck,
DisplaySwapMapping, DisplayTransaction3). The QEMU shell is
transport-agnostic: it forwards MMIO reads/writes verbatim,
so new opcodes introduced upstream in the library require
no QEMU change.

Trace events `apple_gfx_read` / `apple_gfx_write` are
added by the companion trace-events patch (9/9) in a
dedicated Linux-port block — the Linux-port block supersedes
upstream's narrower `apple-gfx.m` definitions with wider
argument types (hwaddr/uint32 vs the Darwin-port's 32-bit
fields). Because `apple-gfx.m` is gated on the `pvg`
appleframeworks dep (macOS hosts only) and is not compiled
on Linux, there is no linker collision.

